<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-745-655  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 745 655.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  July 1989 v40 n7 p31(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software copying policies of the Fortune 500.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Athey, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One hundred of the Fortune 500 companies responded to an 11-itemsurvey focusing on the question: Are companies adopting softwarecopying policies and do they enforce them? When adequately policedand enforced, such policies remove the employer from legalresponsibility for an employee's copying activities.andP;  Of the 100usable responses to the survey, only 13 companies reported havingno policies on copying software for use at work.andP;  Twenty-sevencompanies had no policy on software copying for take-home work and32 companies had no policy on software copying for personal use.andO;Nearly 70 percent of companies reported that a high-rankinginformation services person is responsible for setting softwarecopying policies.andP;  The most popular means of enforcing policy isby internal auditing in which floppy and hard disks are comparedfor original copies or site licenses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software PiracyCompaniesPolicySurvey.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Number of PCs used in organizations. (table)Techniques for informing users. (table)Policy enforcement methods. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>